article.description: Dana Cherry and Rudy Vaden each scored 14 points to help No. 10 Arkansas defeat No. 12 South Carolina, 67-58.
article.headline: South Carolina commits 28 turnovers
article.linkText: Gamecocks' run doomed by turnovers vs. Arkansas
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- South Carolina head coach Susan
Walvius' team saw Arkansas lose to No. 1 Duke, 74-72 in overtime,
in November during the Paradise Jam in the U.S. Virgin Islands, so
she knew her team would have a hard time getting a win when it
faced the Lady Razorbacks.

	   But 28 turnovers by the crippled the Lady Gamecocks'
effort Sunday, and they fell, 67-58, to Arkansas (No. 10 ESPN/USA Today, No. 11 AP).

	   "I think for 30 minutes of the game we played well,'' Walvius
said. "But we can't turn over the ball 28 times and win. In the
close basketball situations we got a little tight and turned it
over down the stretch.''

	   South Carolina (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) played harder than Duke, Arkansas head coach Gary
Blair said.

	   "I've been talking about this game for six months,'' Blair
said. "I'm tired of talking about South Carolina, I was ready to
play it.''

	   Dana Cherry and Ruby Vaden each scored 14 points for Arkansas in
the Lady Razorbacks' Southeastern Conference opener.

	   Jocelyn Penn of South Carolina, the nation's leading scorer,
averaged 27 points entering the game but managed just 19 points
against Arkansas, though she did pull down 13 rebounds. Koretha
Johnson added 15 points for the Lady Gamecocks.

	   "Cherry was guarding her in the second half,'' Blair said.
"She did a good job but got beat a couple of times, but you're
supposed to get beat against the nation's leading scorer.''

	   The win was Blair's 400th career victory.

	   Blair said he was pleased with his post players -- Vaden and
Katrina Nesby -- because they hadn't been scoring from the low
position. Nesby scored four points and had two crucial rebounds in
the team.

	   In the last minute of play, South Carolina committed four fouls
under its basket, allowing Arkansas (14-2, 1-0 SEC) to add six
points to a 61-55 lead.

	   The Lady Gamecocks (13-2, 1-1) started the game with a 7-2 run,
but a steal and layup from Cherry brought the Lady Razorbacks to
9-6.

	   The Lady Razorbacks took a 21-20 lead when Vaden scored inside.
But the lead was short-lived as Sarah Burgess hit a 3-pointer for a
23-21 lead.

	   Cherry scored four points in the closing seconds of the first
half to tie the game at 29 going into halftime.

	   Arkansas took a 35-31 lead early in the second half with a pair
of free throws and a jumper from Shameka Christon.

	   The Lady Gamecocks stayed close until Kelly Morrone knocked down
a 3-pointer from the baseline to give South Carolina a 46-44 lead.

	   "When she fired that thing in the second half and got ... a
lead, it wasn't looking good for the good guys, but we found a way,
and that's what home court is about,'' Blair said.

	   Arkansas came back and eventually took a 59-55 with just under
two minutes to play.

	   Christon and Lewis contributed 13 points for the Lady
Razorbacks.
